<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-112-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 112 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  Feb 12 1990 n3145 p90(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Diamonds could be high tech's best friend. (crystal films promisesuper-fast chips)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carey, John; McWilliams, Gary; Gross, Neil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers are making synthetic diamond films and using them tomake diamond-coated cutting tools, diamond-coated lenses, diamondheat sinks for hot-running electronics and x-ray windows forelectron microscopes.andP;  Sumitomo, a Japanese company, has builtsimple transistors and light-emitting diodes with the material.andO;Diamond films are made by a method called chemical vapordeposition (CVD).andP;  A carbon-containing substance, such as methane,is heated to 400C and combined with hydrogen gas; when the vaporreaches a certain level of concentration, diamond crystals form.andO;Adding the right impurities to the crystal produces a betterconductor than silicon.andP;  Researchers continue to look for ways toproduce single-crystal films on silicon.andP;  Japanese companies areparticularly interested in the possibilities of the diamondcircuit chip.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor industryResearch and DevelopmentCircuit DesignIntegrated CircuitsSemiconductor PreparationHigh Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Finding uses for diamond films. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>